## Background and Motivation

See https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/78887. We want to add support for file-based apps to MSBuildWorkspace, so that users of it (like dotnet-format) can support file-based apps in a simple way.

## Proposed API

### Option A: reuse existing API

(The documentation could be improved, this is just for illustrative purposes.)

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.MSBuild;

 public sealed class MSBuildWorkspace : Workspace
 {
     /// <summary>
     /// Open a project file and all referenced projects.
+    /// Supports file-based apps too (just pass the path to the C# file as <paramref name="projectFilePath"/>).
     /// </summary>
     /// <param name="projectFilePath">The path to the project file to be opened. This may be an absolute path or a path relative to the
     /// current working directory.</param>
     /// <param name="progress">An optional <see cref="IProgress{T}"/> that will receive updates as the project is opened.</param>
     /// <param name="cancellationToken">An optional <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to allow cancellation of this operation.</param>
     public Task<Project> OpenProjectAsync(string projectFilePath, IProgress<ProjectLoadProgress>? progress = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);

     /// <summary>
     /// Open a project file and all referenced projects.
+    /// Supports file-based apps too (just pass the path to the C# file as <paramref name="projectFilePath"/>).
     /// </summary>
     /// <param name="projectFilePath">The path to the project file to be opened. This may be an absolute path or a path relative to the
     /// current working directory.</param>
     /// <param name="progress">An optional <see cref="IProgress{T}"/> that will receive updates as the project is opened.</param>
     /// <param name="msbuildLogger">An optional <see cref="ILogger"/> that will log msbuild results..</param>
     /// <param name="cancellationToken">An optional <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to allow cancellation of this operation.</param>
     public Task<Project> OpenProjectAsync(string projectFilePath, ILogger? msbuildLogger, IProgress<ProjectLoadProgress>? progress = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
 }
```

### Option B: add new API

```diff
 namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.MSBuild;

 public sealed class MSBuildWorkspace : Workspace
 {
+    /// <inheritdoc cref="OpenFileBasedApp(string,ILogger,IProgress<ProjectLoadProgress>,CancellationToken)"/>
+    public Task<Project> OpenFileBasedApp(string entryPointFilePath, IProgress<ProjectLoadProgress>? progress = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);

+    /// <summary>
+    /// Open a file-based app virtual project and all referenced projects.
+    /// </summary>
+    /// <param name="entryPointFilePath">The path to the entry point file of the file-based app to be opened. This may be an absolute path or a path relative to the
+    /// current working directory.</param>
+    /// <param name="progress">An optional <see cref="IProgress{T}"/> that will receive updates as the project is opened.</param>
+    /// <param name="msbuildLogger">An optional <see cref="ILogger"/> that will log msbuild results..</param>
+    /// <param name="cancellationToken">An optional <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to allow cancellation of this operation.</param>
+    public Task<Project> OpenFileBasedApp(string entryPointFilePath, ILogger? msbuildLogger, IProgress<ProjectLoadProgress>? progress = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
 }
```

## Usage Examples

``` C#
var workspace = MSBuildWorkspace.Create();
var project = await workspace.OpenProjectAsync("file.cs");

// Assert that there are no compilation errors.
var compilation = await project.GetCompilationAsync();
compilation.GetDiagnostics().Where(d => d.Severity > DiagnosticSeverity.Hidden).Verify();
```

A prototype of real usage in dotnet-format: https://github.com/dotnet/sdk/compare/main...jjonescz:dotnet-sdk:49285-sprint-format

## Alternative Designs

See options above.

## Risks

Option A doesn't have a way to "disable" file-based app support. Should `MSBuildProjectLoader.AssociateFileExtensionWithLanguage` play a role here?

Option B means the caller (who wants to support both normal projects and file-based apps) needs to somehow decide what's a file-based app and branch accordingly.

**Version Used**: 06488a7a0d5a4c0f27e2fa1dd8cefc2b9dc70a29

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Put this test into src\Workspaces\MSBuild\Test\NetCoreTests.cs:

```cs
    [ConditionalFact(typeof(DotNetSdkMSBuildInstalled))]
    [Trait(Traits.Feature, Traits.Features.MSBuildWorkspace)]
    [Trait(Traits.Feature, Traits.Features.NetCore)]
    public async Task TestOpenProject_ReferenceSelf()
    {
        CreateFiles(new FileSet(
            ("Program.csproj", """
                <Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
                  <PropertyGroup>
                    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
                    <TargetFramework>net6.0</TargetFramework>
                  </PropertyGroup>
                  <ItemGroup>
                    <ProjectReference Include="Program.csproj" />
                  </ItemGroup>
                </Project>
                """),
            ("Program.cs", """
                Console.WriteLine("Hello");
                """)));

        var sourceFilePath = GetSolutionFileName("Program.csproj");

        using var workspace = CreateMSBuildWorkspace();
        var project = await workspace.OpenProjectAsync(sourceFilePath);

        Assert.Empty(workspace.Diagnostics);

        Assert.Equal(["Program"], workspace.CurrentSolution.Projects.Select(p => p.Name).Order());

        var projRef = Assert.Single(project.ProjectReferences);
        Assert.Equal(projRef.ProjectId, workspace.CurrentSolution.Projects.Single().Id);

        var compilation = await project.GetCompilationAsync(); // hangs here
        compilation.GetDiagnostics().Where(d => d.Severity > DiagnosticSeverity.Hidden).Verify();
    }
```

**Expected Behavior**: Succeeds or fails with some exception.

**Actual Behavior**: Hangs for what seems like infinitely on the line that calls `GetCompilationAsync`.
